                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d182">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">883.05/161: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Davis</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-06-11T17:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 11, 1920—5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>637. Your important 862, May 28, 5 p.m. In view of statement that Mixed Tribunals
                    will soon adjourn, and information from Cairo that resignation of Judge Tuck
                    will not become effective until November 1st, also the proposal to reorganize
                    Mixed Courts, the Department will not press for appointment of successor to Tuck
                    at this time. You should make it clear to British Government, however, that in
                    taking this position this Government in no way foregoes its right to nominate a
                    successor to Judge Tuck, nor does it in any way commit itself to any proposed
                    reorganization of the Mixed Court[s] which would contemplate placing this
                    Government in a less favorable position than it now enjoys in Egypt.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Colby</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
